[{"id":40257,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$190 \\mathrm{~V}$","$-190 \\mathrm{~V}$","$-10 \\mathrm{~V}$","$10 \\mathrm{~V}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$e=-\\frac{d \\phi}{d t}=-(20 t-50)=-10$ volt","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":40150,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi b^2}{2 a}$","$\\frac{\\mu_o}{2 \\pi} \\cdot \\frac{b^2}{a}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi} \\cdot \\frac{a^2}{b}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi a^2}{2 b}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\phi=\\mathrm{Mi}=\\mathrm{BA} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{Mi}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{i}}{2 \\mathrm{~b}} \\pi \\mathrm{a}^2 \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{M}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi \\mathrm{a}^2}{2 \\mathrm{~b}}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40139,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["\\(\\varepsilon_1=-L_1 \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_2}{d t}-\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_1}{d t}\\)","\\(\\varepsilon_1=-L_1 \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_1}{d t}-\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_2}{d t}\\)","\\(\\varepsilon_1=-L_1 \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_1}{d t}-\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_1}{d t}\\)","\\(\\varepsilon_1=-L_1 \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_1}{d t}+\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}_2}{\\mathrm{dt}}\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\phi_1=\\mathrm{L}_1 \\mathrm{I}_1+\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\mathrm{I}_2 \\\\ & \\varepsilon_1=-\\frac{\\mathrm{d} \\phi_1}{\\mathrm{dt}}=-\\mathrm{L}_1 \\frac{\\mathrm{dI}}{1} \\frac{\\mathrm{I}_{12}}{\\mathrm{dt}}-\\mathrm{M}_{12} \\frac{\\mathrm{~d} I_2}{\\mathrm{dt}}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40132,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$C_{1}$ moves away from $C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ moves towards $C_{2}$","$C_{1}$ and $C_{3}$ move with equal speeds away from $C_{2}$","$C_{1}$ moves towards $C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ moves away from $C_{2}$","$C_{1}$ and $C_{3}$ move with equal speeds towards $C_{2}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Let the common axis be the z-axis.<br>$C_1$ is at $z = -d$, $C_2$ is at $z = 0$, and $C_3$ is at $z = +d$.<br>Current in $C_1$ is anti-clockwise (ACW), producing a magnetic field $B_1$ in the $+z$ direction at $C_2$.<br>Current in $C_3$ is clockwise (CW), producing a magnetic field $B_3$ in the $-z$ direction at $C_2$.<br>The net magnetic field at $C_2$ is $B_{net} = B_1 - B_3$. Since $C_1$ and $C_3$ are equidistant and carry equal current, initially $B_{net} = 0$.<br><br>To induce a clockwise current in $C_2$, Lenz's law states that the induced current must oppose the change in flux. A clockwise induced current produces a magnetic field in the $-z$ direction.<br>This happens if there is an increasing flux in the $+z$ direction or a decreasing flux in the $-z$ direction.<br><br>Case 1: $C_1$ moves towards $C_2$. The distance decreases, so $B_1$ (in $+z$ direction) increases. This causes an increasing flux in the $+z$ direction.<br><br>Case 2: $C_3$ moves away from $C_2$. The distance increases, so $B_3$ (in $-z$ direction) decreases. This causes a decreasing flux in the $-z$ direction.<br><br>Both actions (moving $C_1$ towards $C_2$ and moving $C_3$ away from $C_2$) result in a net change in flux that induces a clockwise current in $C_2$ to oppose the change.<br>Therefore, option (3) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40249,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["development of air current when the plate is placed.","induction of electrical charge on the plate","shielding of magnetic lines of force as aluminium is a paramagnetic material.","electromagnetic induction in the aluminium plate giving rise to electromagnetic damping."],"answer":3,"solution":"Oscillating coil produces time variable magnetic field. It cause eddy current in the aluminium plate which causes anti-torque on the coil, due to which is stops.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":40184,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Given:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>at</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>.</p><p>Magnetic field will decrease linearly as given below. We can say, value of magnetic field at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>will&#160;be</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></math>.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/435e5f2f-d67d-4ffc-8792-8dbf3a9aea8d-9884753.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 245px;\" /></p><p>Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mtext>ind&#160;</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mfenced><mi>B</mi></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>10</mn><msqrt><mi>&#960;</mi></msqrt></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40158,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6cc14ab6-3a8c-44cb-84af-b3d461f7efac.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 266px;\"/></p><p>The area vector for the square loop is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>According to the above diagram, the magnetic field is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p><p>Hence, the magnitude of induced emf can be calculated as follows</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>e</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi>Δ</mi><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Δ</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced><mo>·</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo> </mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40227,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["decreases by a factor of 9","increases by a factor of 27","increases by a factor of 3","decreases by a factor of $9 \\sqrt{3}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"As total length $L$ of the wire will remain constant\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\mathrm{L}=(3 \\mathrm{a}) \\mathrm{N} \\quad(\\mathrm{N}=\\text { total turns })\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\nand length of winding $=(\\mathrm{d}) \\mathrm{N}$\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/AwhDsCHiFGmqnF3aQf06y5-65Q23Nslyy8btneTYKEo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\r\n\r\n(d = diameter of wire)\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\begin{array}{l}\r\n\r\n\\text { self inductance }=\\mu_{0} \\mathrm{n}^{2} \\mathrm{~A} \\ell \\\\\r\n\r\n\\quad=\\mu_{0} \\mathrm{n}^{2}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{a}^{2}}{4}\\right) \\mathrm{d} \\mathrm{N} \\\\\r\n\r\n\\quad \\propto \\mathrm{a}^{2} \\mathrm{~N} \\propto \\mathrm{a}\\left[\\text { as } \\mathrm{N}=\\mathrm{L} / 3 \\mathrm{a} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{N} \\propto \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{a}}\\right]\r\n\r\n\\end{array}\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\nNow 'a' increased to ' $3 \\mathrm{a}$ ' So self inductance will become 3 times","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40166,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The data given is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>It is given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Area of the loop is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>R</mi><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>d</mi><mi>R</mi></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mstyle></mfrac></math></p><p>The flux is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>R</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>B</mi></math></p><p>So, the magnitude of emf is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>028</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;V</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40199,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The EMF&nbsp;is induced in the coil when it is moving&nbsp;in a uniform magnetic field,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>l</mi></math>&nbsp;and the current,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40261,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$-\\frac{W_2-W_1}{5 R n t}$","$-\\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{W}_2-\\mathrm{W}_1\\right)}{5 \\mathrm{Rt}}$","$-\\frac{W_2-W_1}{\\text { Rnt }}$","$-\\frac{\\mathrm{n}\\left(\\mathrm{W}_2-\\mathrm{W}_1\\right)}{\\mathrm{Rt}}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{I}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{I}}{\\mathrm{R}^{\\prime}} \\frac{\\mathrm{d} \\phi}{\\mathrm{dt}}$\nor, I $=-\\frac{1}{R^{\\prime}} \\mathrm{n}\\left[\\frac{\\mathrm{W}_2-\\mathrm{W}_1}{\\mathrm{t}_2-\\mathrm{t}_1}\\right]$\n( $W_1$ and $W_2$ are not the magnetic field, but the values of flux associated with one turn of coil) $I=\\frac{-1}{(R+4 R)} \\frac{n\\left(W_2-W_1\\right)}{t}$\nor, $\\mathrm{I}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{n}\\left(\\mathrm{W}_2-\\mathrm{W}_1\\right)}{5 \\mathrm{Rt}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":40206,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> are connected, then the steady state current in the inductor <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> are connected then current through inductor remains same. So potential difference across <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40204,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Emf</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>NAsin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Emf</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B&#969;NA</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B&#969;N</mi><mfenced><msup><mi>&#960;R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mn>50</mn></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mn>20</mn></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>64</mn><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40187,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>It is given that magnetic flux&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>For magnetic flux to be zero&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>According to Faraday&#39;s law of electromagnetic induction,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Heat produced from&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mfrac><msup><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40136,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$5.7 \\times 10^{-2}$","$7.5 \\times 10^{-2}$","$7.5 \\times 10^{-3}$","$5.7 \\times 10^{-3}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given: $l = 1$ m, $B = 0.10$ T, $R = 2$ Ω, $v = 1.5$ m/s<br>Motional EMF: $\\varepsilon = Blv = 0.10 \\times 1 \\times 1.5 = 0.15$ V<br>Current: $I = \\frac{\\varepsilon}{R} = \\frac{0.15}{2} = 0.075$ A<br>Magnetic force on rod: $F = BIl = 0.10 \\times 0.075 \\times 1 = 7.5 \\times 10^{-3}$ N<br>For constant velocity, applied force equals magnetic force.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40146,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Case-I:\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40ICr09IOfMfea6ofQ8WIVFtA51c8p0h2VXGoKZWvG8.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$i=\\frac{20}{R} \\Rightarrow R=4 \\Omega$\nCase-II:<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aYHJcavg8RiqhaKYu2Ea7SeQVrTZ5q8hqb7-fDs1Rac.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{i}=\\frac{20}{\\mathrm{Z}} \\\\ & 4=\\frac{20}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{R}^2+\\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{L}}^2}} \\Rightarrow \\sqrt{\\mathrm{R}^2+\\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{L}}^2}=5 \\\\ & \\mathrm{R}^2+\\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{L}}^2=25 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{L}}=3 \\Omega \\\\ & \\mathrm{L}=\\frac{3}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{f}}=\\frac{1}{2 \\times 50}=\\frac{1000}{100} \\mathrm{mH} \\\\ & \\mathrm{L}=10 \\mathrm{mH}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40125,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$36$","$128\\sqrt{2}$","$16$","$64$"],"answer":0,"solution":"The induced emf in the coil is given by Faraday's law:<br><br>$E = N A \\dfrac{dB}{dt}$<br><br>The resistance of the coil is $R = \\rho \\dfrac{l}{a}$, where $l$ is the total length of the wire and $a$ is its cross-sectional area.<br><br>The length of the wire is $l = N (2\\pi R_c)$, where $R_c$ is the radius of the coil. Since the area of the coil is $A = \\pi R_c^2$, we have $R_c = \\sqrt{\\dfrac{A}{\\pi}}$.<br><br>Thus, $l = 2N\\sqrt{\\pi A}$.<br><br>The cross-sectional area of the wire is $a = \\pi r^2$.<br><br>Therefore, the resistance is:<br><br>$R = \\rho \\dfrac{2N\\sqrt{\\pi A}}{\\pi r^2} \\propto \\dfrac{N\\sqrt{A}}{r^2}$<br><br>The power dissipated in the coil is:<br><br>$P = \\dfrac{E^2}{R} \\propto \\dfrac{(N A)^2}{\\dfrac{N\\sqrt{A}}{r^2}} = N A^{3/2} r^2$<br><br>For the second coil, the parameters are $N' = 2N$, $A' = 2A$, and $r' = 3r$. The new power dissipated is:<br><br>$P' = P \\left(\\dfrac{2N}{N}\\right) \\left(\\dfrac{2A}{A}\\right)^{3/2} \\left(\\dfrac{3r}{r}\\right)^2$<br><br>$P' = P (2) (2\\sqrt{2}) (9) = 36\\sqrt{2} P$<br><br>Given that $P' = \\sqrt{2}\\alpha P$, we can compare the expressions to find:<br><br>$\\sqrt{2}\\alpha = 36\\sqrt{2} \\Rightarrow \\alpha = 36$<br><br>Answer: $36$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40144,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Y9TtPaGnAAY_L86pujzws5V_CW1SlymGcLv2waeMtxw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/L8-8fUEkdr6fH1PSfA8GHjV1UoqP6ji8xR6TV0q8hRs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ToJqUwk4u-YAfIRWg2kvoV5cUmrTz_I9P_ZaXbAMNk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/w5w0mwTKHWcvIwpdvtVhL2Htfxn-MSSBNOYVxQZ75bw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tYhiac6tfHZFYE59qDhjwLuJbnZKQO-wcdElCwzWiMo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$\\begin{aligned} & E=-\\frac{d \\phi}{d t} \\\\ & \\phi=B b x \\\\ & |E|=B b v\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40259,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$0.05 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.1 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.15 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.3 \\mathrm{~s}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{I}=\\mathrm{I}_{\\circ}\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{L}}\\mathrm{t}}\\right)$\n$0.693=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{L}} \\mathrm{t}$\n$\\mathrm{t}=\\frac{.3 \\times 0.693}{2}=0.1 \\mathrm{sec}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":40200,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["parallel to the plane of coil and increasing with time","outward and increasing with time","outward and decreasing with time","parallel to the plane of coil and decreasing with time"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Lenz&#39;s&nbsp;law state that the direction of the induced current is such that it opposes its cause of generation, so,&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f06837a1-9753-4b36-b74c-b777081d41fc-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>,&nbsp;must not be parallel to the plane of coil for non-zero flux and according to Lenz&#39;s&nbsp;law if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> is outward it should be decreasing for anticlockwise induced current.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40205,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>|</mo><mi>&#1013;</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>|</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>|</mo><mi>&#1013;</mi><mo>|</mo></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math></p><p>At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>|</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40240,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c65db82-09be-495b-9148-7f28c397e5f1-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 207px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ce0eb965-a4a6-4c60-adb2-6af55ab79eb6-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 208px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0bed11c9-4111-4d3a-bf82-acc84966d221-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 207px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b6a224a9-6be2-4895-9f6f-0571232393e1-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 214px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>for&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>R</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mi>&#945;</mi><mi>r</mi></math></p><p>for&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>R</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mi>&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bbba8497-c714-48c1-b600-b8dd57cf7ee3-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 227px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40258,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{B}\\ell \\mathrm{V}$","$-\\mathrm{B}\\ell \\mathrm{V}$","zero","$2 \\mathrm{B}\\ell \\mathrm{V}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\left|\\frac{d \\phi}{d t}\\right|=2 B \\ell v$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":40260,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$C=4 \\mu F$","$C=8 \\mu F$","$C=1 \\mu F$","$C=2 \\mu F$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$f=\\frac{1}{2 \\pi \\sqrt{L C}}$\n$C=\\frac{1}{4 \\times \\pi^2 f^2 \\times 10}$\n$C=1 \\mu F$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":40238,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mtext>1</mtext><mtext>.67&#160;H</mtext></mrow> </math>","<math > <mrow>  <mtext>6&#x00A0;H</mtext></mrow></math>","<math > <mrow>  <mtext>3&#x00A0;H</mtext></mrow></math>","<math > <mrow>  <mtext>0</mtext><mtext>.67&#x00A0;H</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Magnetic flux<br /><br /><math><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>I</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∴</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>ε</mi><mi>ind</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>average</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>0.1</mn></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.67</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mn>H</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40183,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>&#969;</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>B</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>&#969;</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>B</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>&#969;</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi><mi>&#969;</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0a133cd-b1e3-492f-b6ce-24ba9f603a69-9893978_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 112px;\" /></p><p>Linear velocity at the distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;from the centre can be written as,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>x</mi></math>.</p><p>Therefore, induced EMF due to small element will be,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></math></p><p>Integrating both sides, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8747;</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8747;</mo><mi>B</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>L</mi></msubsup><mi>x</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40229,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>637.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>740</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>437.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>540</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Induced emf / back emf in an inductor coil is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#949;</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Ldi</mi><mi>dt</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>25</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>25</mn><mn>15</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math><br /><br />Energy of inductor is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>Li</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Energy change&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#9651;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mfenced><mrow><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>625</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>437</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40168,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The data given is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>R</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>Using Ohm&#39;s law,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>R</mi></math>,</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>The energy of an inductor is given by&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>25</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>625</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40215,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathv